@node NEWB "Template/ New Bitmap Font..."

@{FG Highlight}Template/ New Bitmap Font...@{FG Text}

This command opens a requester to set the size for a new bitmap font.
Choose a size from the requester and then TypeSmith will automatically
generate bitmap characters based on the actual character outlines. These
bitmaps will require hand-tuning, but will provide a good starting point.

If you later create or change a character outline and want to
automatically generate a bitmap for that character without creating a
whole new bitmap font, choose the @{"Generate Character" link GENC}
command.

@{FG Highlight}Requester Gadgets:@{FG Text}

@{U}Bitmap Font Size@{UU}: Choose a size from those listed for the new
bitmap font.

@{U}User Point Size@{UU}: Enter a size for the new bitmap font.
@prev GENC
@endnode

@node OPEN "Template/ Open ģ"

@{FG Highlight}Template/ Open ģ"

This command allows you to open existing bitmap fonts and templates.

You must have an active window containing a font outline before opening a
bitmap font or bitmap picture.

See also:
@{" Open ģ IFF ILBM Template...           " link OIFF}
@{" Open ģ Amiga Bitmap Font...           " link OAMI}
@{" Open ģ Soft-Logik Bitmap Font...      " link OSOF}
@{" Open ģ PostScript ABF Screen Font...  " link OABF}
@{" Open ģ Subscribe IFF ILBM Template... " link SUBS}
@endnode

@node OIFF "Template/ Open ģ IFF ILBM Template..."

@{FG Highlight}Template/ Open ģ IFF ILBM Template...@{FG Text}

This command allows you to load a bitmap picture into the bitmap template.
The template can be used as a guide over which you can draw your
character. This is useful if you have a scanned example of your character.
Any type of IFF ILBM picture can be imported except CMYK pictures.

This command will open a file requester to select a picture file to
import. The file must be in IFF ILBM format. Choose a file and click on
the Ok gadget. TypeSmith will load the picture and will open a requester
to set the import option.

Specify whether to import the picture at its original size, scale it to
fit in the character window, or to paste it to any size. Scaling a picture
to fit will change its horizontal and vertical size to match the character
window. This may distort the aspect ratio.

After the bitmap picture appears, you can drag it and resize it at any
time with the mouse pointer just as you would a character path. You cannot
edit the bitmap picture or manipulate it with any other TypeSmith command
except @{"Autotrace" link TRAC}.

Bitmap pictures are shown in the background of the current character
window when the @{"Show Template" link TypeSmith:Help/English/vie/SHWT} command or @{"Show Template" link TypeSmith:Help/English/too/STEM} tool are selected.
If the command and tool are not selected when a bitmap picture is
imported, they will be toggled on automatically.

IMPORTANT! Bitmap fonts and bitmap pictures share the template layer in
TypeSmith. Loading a bitmap template clears the bitmap for that character,
and thus you can no longer save the bitmap characters as a font file. You
will have to reopen the bitmap font file to clear the bitmap picture from
the template layer.

@{FG Highlight}Requester Gadgets:@{FG Text}

@{U}Original Size@{UU}: Import the picture at its original size and aspect
ratio.

@{U}Frame to Scale@{UU}: Paste the picture into the window at any size by
dragging it.

@{U}Scale to Fit@{UU}: Automatically scale the picture to fill the window.
@endnode

@node OAMI "Template/ Open ģ Amiga Bitmap Font..."

@{FG Highlight}Template/ Open ģ Soft-Logik Bitmap Font...@{FG Text}

This command allows you to open an AmigaDOS format bitmap font. It will
open a file requester to select an Amiga bitmap font and size to open.
TypeSmith is capable of opening standard bitmap fonts, but is not
compatible with colorfonts.

Bitmap fonts are shown on the bitmap template for the outline font. You
can toggle the display of the bitmap layer by choosing the @{"Show Template" link TypeSmith:Help/English/too/STEM}
tool or by choosing the @{"Show Template" link TypeSmith:Help/English/vie/SHWT} command. You can edit the bitmap
font with the @{"Edit" link EDIT} command.
@endnode

@node OSOF "Template/ Open ģ Soft-Logik Bitmap Font..."

@{FG Highlight}Template/ Open ģ Soft-Logik Bitmap Font...@{FG Text}

This command allows you to open a Soft-Logik format bitmap font. It will
open a file requester to select a font file to open.

Soft-Logik format bitmap fonts normally have the following file extensions:

.##I: Amiga format interlace mode
.##N: Amiga format non-interlace mode
.##H: Atari format high-resolution mode
.##M: Atari format medium-resolution mode
- where ## is the size of the bitmap font.

The difference between the modes is the aspect ratio used when designing
the font. TypeSmith will create only Amiga interlace fonts, but any format
can be loaded.

Bitmap fonts are shown on the bitmap template for the outline font. You
can toggle the display of the bitmap layer by choosing the @{"Show Template" link TypeSmith:Help/English/too/STEM}
tool or by choosing the @{"Show Template" link TypeSmith:Help/English/vie/SHWT} command. You can edit the bitmap
font with the @{"Edit" link EDIT} command.
@endnode

@node OABF "Template/ Open ģ PostScript ABF Screen Font..."

@{FG Highlight}Template/ Open ģ PostScript ABF Screen Font...@{FG Text}

This command allows you to open a PostScript Type 1 format bitmap font. It
will open a file requester to select a font file to open.

PostScript Type 1 format bitmap fonts normally have the following file
extensions:

.ABF
.##  - where ## is the size of the bitmap font.

Bitmap fonts are shown on the bitmap template for the outline font. You
can toggle the display of the bitmap layer by choosing the @{"Show Template" link TypeSmith:Help/English/too/STEM}
tool or by choosing the @{"Show Template" link TypeSmith:Help/English/vie/SHWT} command. You can edit the bitmap
font with the @{"Edit" link EDIT} command.

Note: FON format fonts may not be opened in TypeSmith.
@endnode

@node SUBS "Template/ Open ģ Subscribe IFF ILBM Template..."

@{FG Highlight}Template/ Open ģ IFF ILBM Template...@{FG Text}

This command allows you to subscribe to a bitmap picture and import it
into the bitmap template. The template can be used as a guide over which
you can draw your character. This is useful if you have a scanned example
of your character. Any type of IFF ILBM picture can be subscribed to
except CMYK pictures.

This will open the HotLinks Subscribe requester to select a picture
edition to import. Choose a file and click on the OK gadget. TypeSmith
will subscribe to the picture and will open a requester to set the import
options.

Specify whether to import the picture at its original size, scale it to
fit in the character window, or to paste it to any size. Scaling a picture
to fit will change its horizontal and vertical size to match the character
window. This may distort the aspect ratio.

After the bitmap picture appears, you can drag it and resize it at any
time with the mouse pointer just as you would a character path. You cannot
edit the bitmap picture or manipulate it with any other TypeSmith command
except @{"Autotrace" link TRAC}.

If the edition is changed in another program while TypeSmith is still
running, it will be updated automatically through Hotlinks.

Bitmap pictures are shown in the background of the current character
window when the @{"Show Template" link TypeSmith:Help/English/vie/SHWT} command or @{"Show Template" link TypeSmith:Help/English/too/STEM}
tool are selected. If the command and tool are not selected when a bitmap
picture is imported, they will be toggled on automatically.

IMPORTANT! Bitmap fonts and bitmap pictures share the template layer in TypeSmith. Loading a bitmap template clears the bitmap for that character, and thus you can no longer save the bitmap characters as a font file. You will have to reopen the bitmap font file to clear the bitmap picture from the template layer.

@{FG Highlight}Requester Gadgets:@{FG Text}

@{U}Original Size@{UU}: Import the picture at its original size and aspect
ratio.

@{U}Frame to Scale@{UU}: Paste the picture into the window at any size by
dragging it.

@{U}Scale to Fit@{UU}: Automatically scale the picture to fill the window.
@endnode

@node SAVE "Template/ Save ģ"

@{FG Highlight}Template/ Save ģ"

This command allows you to save the current bitmap font or template.

If the current character has an IFF ILBM template, the Open ģ IFF ILBM
Template command will be available. If a bitmap font is open and you have
not imported a bitmap template, you can save the bitmap font in any of the
available formats.

See also:
@{" Save ģ IFF ILBM Template...          " link SIFF}
@{" Save ģ Amiga Bitmap Font...          " link SAMI}
@{" Save ģ Soft-Logik Bitmap Font...     " link SSOF}
@{" Save ģ PostScript ABF Screen Font... " link SABF}
@{" Save ģ Publish IFF ILBM Template...  " link PUBL}
@endnode

@node SIFF "Template/ Save ģ IFF ILBM Template..."

@{FG Highlight}Template/ Save ģ IFF ILBM Template...@{FG Text}

This command allows you to save the current bitmap template as an IFF ILBM
picture. It will only be available if the current character has a bitmap
template.

This command will open a file requester to choose a name and filepath for
the picture.
@endnode

@node SAMI "Template/ Save ģ Amiga Bitmap Font..."

@{FG Highlight}Template/ Save ģ Soft-Logik Bitmap Font...@{FG Text}

This command allows you to save the current bitmap font as an AmigaDOS
format bitmap font. It will open a file requester to select a name and
filepath for the font.

This command will only be available if a bitmap font is open and if you
have not imported a bitmap picture template.

AmigaDOS bitmap fonts are normally stored in the FONTS: directory.
@endnode

@node SSOF "Template/ Save ģ Soft-Logik Bitmap Font..."

@{FG Highlight}Template/ Save ģ Soft-Logik Bitmap Font...@{FG Text}

This command allows you to save a Soft-Logik format bitmap font. It will
open a file requester to select a font name and filepath.

This command will only be available if a bitmap font is open and if you
have not imported a bitmap picture template.

Soft-Logik format bitmap fonts created with TypeSmith normally have a .##I
file extension, where I stands for interlace and ## is the size of the
font file. You can use any file extension you wish, since PageStream is
not name sensitive.
@endnode

@node SABF "Template/ Save ģ PostScript ABF Screen Font..."

@{FG Highlight}Template/ Save ģ PostScript ABF Screen Font...@{FG Text}

This command allows you to save a PostScript Type 1 format bitmap font. It
will open a file requester to select a font name and filepath for the font.

This command will only be available if a bitmap font is open and if you
have not imported a bitmap picture template.

PostScript Type 1 format bitmap fonts normally have the following file
extensions, but you can use any file extension you want.

.ABF
.##  - where ## is the size of the bitmap font.
@endnode

@node PUBL "Template/ Save ģ Publish IFF ILBM Template..."

@{FG Highlight}Template/ Save ģ Publish IFF ILBM Template...@{FG Text}

This command allows you to publish the current bitmap template as an
edition. It will only be available if the current character has a bitmap
template, and if you did not subscribe to the picture.

This command will open a requester to choose an name for the picture
edition.
@endnode

@node EDIT "Template/ Edit"

@{FG Highlight}Template/ Edit@{FG Text}

This command allows you to edit the bitmap template for the current
character when a bitmap font is open. It is equivalent to choosing the
@{"Edit Bitmap" link TypeSmith:Help/English/too/EDIT} tool from the toolbox. You cannot edit bitmap pictures,
only bitmap fonts.

Choosing the Edit command or tool toggles the bitmap grid. When the tool
is depressed, or when the command has a checkmark next to it in the menu,
you can edit the bitmap font (if one is open).

The bitmap editing mode provides a standard paint mode like a paint
program. When you paint a white dot, it will change to black, and vice
versa. Clicking changes just one dot, while dragging changes all the dots
touched by the pointer.

To move the entire character within the boundaries of the bitmap
character, hold down a Shift key and press one of the arrow keys.
@endnode

@node CLEA "Template/ Clear"

@{FG Highlight}Template/ Clear@{FG Text}

This command clears the bitmap font and/or template from memory.
@endnode

@node TRAC "Template/ Autotrace..."

@{FG Highlight}Template/ Autotrace...@{FG Text}

This command opens a requester to set options for tracing a picture.
Autotracing converts a bitmap picture into paths that can be used as part
of a character. For example, you could start your character as a
hand-drawn sketch. Then you could scan it, import it as a picture and
autotrace it.

This feature is intended to provide you with an approximation of a
character outline based on an imported picture, but you should hand-edit
it to create the final character outline.

@{FG Highlight}Requester Gadgets:@{FG Text}

@{U}Normal@{UU}: Creates the simplest trace and is the fastest.

@{U}Medium@{UU}: Medium accuracy and speed.

@{U}Accurate@{UU}: Creates more points but is slower.

TypeSmith will open a status requester to show the progress of the tracing
process.
@endnode

@node GENC "Template/ Generate Character"

@{FG Highlight}Template/ Generate Character@{FG Text}

If after creating a bitmap font, you later create or change a character
outline and want to automatically generate a bitmap for that character
with this command.

Generate Character creates a bitmap character for the current character
only.

See also:
@{" New Bitmap Font... " link NEWB}
@next NEWB
@endnode
